Term Deposit Subscription Prediction¶

Introduction¶

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a Portuguese banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be ('yes') or not ('no') subscribed.

Domain¶

Business

Goal¶

Using the data collected from existing customers, build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio

Observation¶

Data types based on the description provided in the problem statement

age       (numeric)     : age of the customer
job       (categorical) : type of job
marital   (categorical) : marital status
education (categorical) : education level
default   (binary)      : has credit in default
balance   (numeric)     : balance in the account
housing   (binary)      : has housing loan
loan      (binary)      : has personal loan


contact   (categorical) : contact communication type
day       (numeric)     : last contact day of the month
month     (categorical) : last contact month of year
duration  (numeric)     : last contact duration, in seconds
campaign  (numeric)     : number of contacts performed during this campaign and for this client
pdays     (numeric)     : number of days that passed by after the client was last contacted from a previous campaign (-1 tells us the person has not been contacted or contact period is beyond 900 days)
previous  (numeric)     : number of contacts performed before this campaign and for this client
poutcome  (categorical) : outcome of the previous marketing campaign


Target    (binary)      : has the client subscribed a term deposit

Based on this, we noticed all the attributes have the right data types.

Strategies to handle data challenges¶

Data Pollution¶

  • The columns under consideration for data pollution are balance and pdays

  • balance - We notice some negative values for balance.
    • Negative Balance - If there are customers with negative balance and have subscribed to Term Deposit, we can safely assume its a data entry error. Its highly unlikely a bank would allow a customer with negative balance to subscribe. A term deposit would require a lock in capital and with negative balance it is not possible. So for those values, we can take the absolute of them to fix it.
    • Zero Balance - Again based on above logic, if there are customers with zero balance and have subscribed to Term Deposit, we can assume its a data entry error. But for this case, we will replace it with median balance.
    • Low Balance - Even after replacing the values, there might be instances where the balance is very low (Eg: 1). But without knowing what was the agreed term deposit amount, its difficult to fix these values. So for the purpose of this project, we will just allow these values to be as is.
  • pdays - We notice negative value (-1) for most of customers. This just means these customers were never contacted or contact period has been more than 900 days. So for these values, we can convert all the -1 to 900, which is the max pdays we are considering

Outliers¶

  • The columns under consideration for outliers are age, balance, duration, pdays, campaign and previous

  • age - We can attempt to bin the values for age to reduce the effect of outliers
  • balance - We can log transform the value, to pull in the outliers
  • duration - We can log transform the value, to pull in the outliers
  • pdays - We can log transform the value, to pull in the outliers
  • campaign - We can log transform the value, to pull in the outliers
  • previous - We can log transform the value, to pull in the outliers

Missing Values¶

  • The columns under consideration for missing values are the categorical columns job, education, contact and poutcome

  • For all the categorical columns, we can replace the missing "unknown" values with the mode of the column.

Logistic Regression and Decision Trees¶

Discussion on Confusion Matrix Terms¶

  • True Positive (TP) (Predicted = 1, Actual = 1)

    Predict that the customer will subscribe to Term Deposit, and they actually did.

  • False Positive (FP) (Predicted = 1, Actual = 0)

    Predict that the customer will subscribe to Term Deposit, but they did not.

  • True Negative (TN) (Predicted = 0, Actual = 0)

    Predict that the customer will not subscribe to Term Deposit, and they did not.

  • False Negative (FN) (Predicted = 0, Actual = 1)

    Predict that the customer will not subscribe to Term Deposit, but they actually did.

Important Metric¶

The goal is to build a model that will help the marketing team identify potential customers who are relatively more likely to subscribe term deposit and thus increase their hit ratio.
Based on this understanding, for this problem, the goal is to increase the number of potential customers that the marketing team can reach out to.
Since the marketing team's hit ratio will go down if FN goes up, the goal is to reduce the number of FN. This is done by improving Recall.

So for any performance improvement, Recall will be the measure that is used for comparison.

def split_data(description, df_to_use, target):
    print("Splitting data for                         : {0}".format(description))
    X = df_to_use
    Y = target
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.30, random_state=my_random_state)
    print("Original Term Deposit Subscribed Values     : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(Y.loc[Y['Target'] == 1]), (len(Y.loc[Y['Target'] == 1])/len(Y.index)) * 100))
    print("Original Term Deposit Not Subscribed Values : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(Y.loc[Y['Target'] == 0]), (len(Y.loc[Y['Target'] == 0])/len(Y.index)) * 100))
    print("")
    print("Training Term Deposit Subscribed Values     : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(y_train[y_train['Target'] == 1]), (len(y_train[y_train['Target'] == 1])/len(y_train)) * 100))
    print("Training Term Deposit Not Subscribed Values : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(y_train[y_train['Target'] == 0]), (len(y_train[y_train['Target'] == 0])/len(y_train)) * 100))
    print("")
    print("Test Term Deposit Subscribed Values         : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(y_test[y_test['Target'] == 1]), (len(y_test[y_test['Target'] == 1])/len(y_test)) * 100))
    print("Test Term Deposit Not Subscribed Values     : {0} ({1:0.2f}%)".format(len(y_test[y_test['Target'] == 0]), (len(y_test[y_test['Target'] == 0])/len(y_test)) * 100))
    return (X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test)

def create_confusion_matrix(axs, row, pos, description, actual, predicted, training_accuracy, testing_accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score, roc_auc_score):
    if axs.ndim > 1:
        axis_heat_map = axs[row][pos]
    else:
        axis_heat_map = axs[pos]

    labels = ["TN","FP","FN","TP"]
    cf = confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    group_labels = ["{}\n\n".format(value) for value in labels]
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])

    stats_text = "\n\nAccuracy(Train) = {:0.3f}\nAccuracy(Test) = {:0.3f}\nPrecision = {:0.3f}\nRecall = {:0.3f}\nF1 Score = {:0.3f}\nROC AUC Score = {:0.3f}\n".format(training_accuracy, testing_accuracy, precision, recall, f1_score, roc_auc_score)
    
    heatmap = sns.heatmap(cf, annot=box_labels, annot_kws={"size": 14}, linewidths=0.5, linecolor='w', fmt="", cmap="Oranges", cbar=False, xticklabels="auto", yticklabels="auto", ax=axis_heat_map, square=True)
    axis_heat_map.set_title(description, fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_ylabel("Actual", fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_xlabel("Predicted" + stats_text, fontsize=14)
    axis_heat_map.set_xticklabels(axis_heat_map.get_xticklabels(), rotation = 45, fontsize = 10)
    axis_heat_map.set_yticklabels(axis_heat_map.get_yticklabels(), rotation = 25, fontsize = 10)
    
    return_list = [value for value in cf.flatten()]
    return return_list

def train_test(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, algo):
    print("******************************** " + description + " ******************************************************")
    print("")
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = split_data(description, df_to_use, target)
    algo.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_predict = algo.predict(X_test)
    training_accuracy = algo.score(X_train,y_train)
    testing_accuracy = algo.score(X_test, y_test)
    precision = precision_score(y_test,y_predict)
    recall = recall_score(y_test,y_predict)
    f1score = f1_score(y_test,y_predict)
    rocscore = roc_auc_score(y_test,y_predict)
    
    cf_list = create_confusion_matrix(axs, row, pos, description, y_test, y_predict, training_accuracy, testing_accuracy, precision, recall, f1score, rocscore)
    
    return_list = [training_accuracy, testing_accuracy, precision, recall, f1score, rocscore]
    return_list = ["{:0.3f}".format(value) for value in return_list]
    return_list = cf_list + return_list
    return_list.insert(0, description)
    
    print("")
    print("********************************************************************************************************")


    return [X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test, algo, y_predict, return_list]

def bagging(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, max_depth, logit=False, dt=True):
    if logit == True:
        bgcl = BaggingClassifier(base_estimator=LogisticRegression(random_state=my_random_state) ,n_estimators=50, max_samples= .7, bootstrap=True, oob_score=True, random_state=my_random_state)
    elif dt == True:
        bgcl = BaggingClassifier(base_estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', max_depth=max_depth, random_state=my_random_state), n_estimators=50, max_samples= .7, bootstrap=True, oob_score=True, random_state=my_random_state)
    return train_test(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, bgcl)

def random_forest(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, max_depth):
    rfcl = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = 50,random_state=my_random_state,max_depth=max_depth,criterion="entropy")
    return train_test(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, rfcl)
In [57]:
def ada_boost(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, max_depth, logit=False, dt=True):
    if logit == True:
        abcl = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator=LogisticRegression(random_state=my_random_state), n_estimators = 50, learning_rate=0.1, random_state=my_random_state)
    elif dt == True:
        abcl = AdaBoostClassifier(base_estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy', max_depth=max_depth, random_state=my_random_state), n_estimators = 50, learning_rate=0.1, random_state=my_random_state)
    return train_test(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, abcl)

def grad_boost(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, max_depth):

    return train_test(axs, row, pos, description, df_to_use, target, gbcl)
